Note that glimpse allows us to also see what kind of variables we are dealing with. Thus glimpse allows us to see that we have four variables within our dataframe: 1) Entity; 2) Code; 3) Year; 4) Life.expectancy.at.birth..historical.

  • Entity is a string or character variable that tells us the country that we are dealing with: âAfghanistanâ, âAlbaniaâ, âAlgeriaâ, etc.
  • Code is also a string or character variable that gives us the country code: âAFGâ, âALBâ, âDZAâ, etc.
  • Year is is a numeric or integer variable: 1950, 1951, 1952, etc.
  • Life.expectancy.at.birth..historical. is a numeric or double precision variable: 27.7, 28.0, 28.4, etc.

5 Creating a scatterplot

Letâs say that we want to create a scatterplot depicting the relationship between urbanization and life expectancy. The first thing we need to do is to calculate averages per country. We will proceed as we did previously.

5.1 Create averages

The next step is to create averages for all the countries. The %>% is called the pipe operator. This operator makes it possible to easily chain a sequence of calculations. âChainingâ means that you invoke multiple method calls. As each method returns an object, you can actually allow the calls to be chained together in a single statement, without needing variables to store the intermediate results.

library(dplyr)
life_expectancy2<-life_expectancy%>%
  group_by(Code)%>%
  summarize(life_expectancy=mean(Life.expectancy.at.birth..historical.))
urbanization2<-urbanization%>%
  group_by(Code)%>%
  summarize(urbanization=mean(Urban.population....of.total.population.))

So we have some unusual entries such as ââ,âOWID_KOSâ or âOWID_WRLâ. What are these countries? We can do a subset to answer this question.

weird_labels <- c("OWID_KOS", "OWID_WRL", "")
weird_countries<-subset(life_expectancy, (Code %in% weird_labels))

Letâs inspect them by verifying unique countries

weird_countries2<-subset(weird_countries, !duplicated(weird_countries$Code))
head(weird_countries2, n=10)
      Entity     Code Year Life.expectancy.at.birth..historical.
73    Africa          1925                                  26.4
9307  Kosovo OWID_KOS 1950                                  57.9
20152  World OWID_WRL 1800                                  28.5

So what is the problem with these data?

The problem is that these are aggregates that were decided by Our World in Data. So, we should remove them from the data. The way to do that is subsetting them based on the names that seemed problematic. Note the difference in code from before !(Code %in% weird_labels) vs.Â (Code %in% weird_labels)

5.3 Cleaning our dataset

weird_labels <- c("OWID_KOS", "OWID_WRL", "")
clean_countries<-subset(life_expectancy2, !(Code %in% weird_labels))
head(clean_countries, n=5)

5 ALB              68.3

Great! Letâs repeat the procedure for urbanization.

5.6 Doing a scatterplot

ggplot2 in R is one of the most elegant and most versatile graphing libraries in R. It implements the grammar of graphics, a coherent system for describing and building graphs. We will start by creating simple scatterplots and use that to introduce aesthetic mappings and geometric objects.

We are finally able to do simple scatterplot.

library(ggplot2)
fig1<-ggplot(new_data2, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()
fig1

5.7 Saving our first plot

We can save our plot by using the following code!

5.7.1 Relative Path Option

ggsave(fig1, file = "./fig1.jpg", 
       height = 20, width = 20, 
       units = "cm", dpi = 300)

5.7.2 Absolute Path Option

6 ggplot options

Let us play a bit with the options in ggplot so that we make our graph nicer.

6.1 Improving X and Y axis labels

fig2<-ggplot(new_data2, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("Urbanization") + ylab("Life Expectancy")
fig2

6.2 Adding a Title

fig2<-ggplot(new_data2, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("Urbanization") + ylab("Life Expectancy")+
  ggtitle("Example Title")
fig2

6.3 Getting rid of the grey background

fig2<-ggplot(new_data2, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("Urbanization") + ylab("Life Expectancy")+
  ggtitle("Example Title")+
  theme_bw()
fig2

6.4 Fitting a line

Let us fit a line to see if there is any relationship between urbanization and life expectancy. Is it the case that countries with higher levels of urbanization also have higher life expectancy?

fig2<-ggplot(new_data2, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("Urbanization") + ylab("Life Expectancy")+
  ggtitle("Example Title")+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=FALSE)

fig2

The blue line would indeed suggest that as the level of urbanization goes up, so does life expectancy.

6.5 Fixing the X and Y axis to particular values

But what if we fixed our axies to particular values. Woudl we still see the same effects?

fig3<-ggplot(new_data2, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("Urbanization") + ylab("Life Expectancy")+
  ggtitle("Example Title")+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=FALSE)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(50,100))+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(50,100))
fig3

6.6 Labelling the data

There are many ways of labeling the data in ggplot. But let us try a simple way.

First let us do a quick left merge so that we keep the original country names

label_cntry<-subset(life_expectancy, select = c("Entity", "Code"))
label_cntry<-subset(label_cntry, !duplicated(Code))
new_data3<-left_join(new_data2, label_cntry, by = c("Code"="Code"))
fig3<-ggplot(new_data3, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("Urbanization") + ylab("Life Expectancy")+
  ggtitle("Example Title")+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=FALSE)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
  geom_text(aes(label = Entity),
            size = 4, 
            check_overlap = TRUE, 
            position = position_nudge(y = 1))
fig3

What if we wanted to do selective labeling? Letâs say, we just want to label Italy and the US. How could we do that?

Well, we could create a new dataset based on a subset and then label the data.

6.7 Subsetting the data to two countries

countries_of_interest = c("Italy", "United States")
italy_us_df<-subset(new_data3, Entity %in%  countries_of_interest)

6.8 Letâs try the labelling again

fig4<-ggplot(new_data3, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("Urbanization") + ylab("Life Expectancy")+
  ggtitle("Example Title")+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=FALSE)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
  geom_text(aes(label = Entity),
            size = 4, 
            check_overlap = TRUE, 
            position = position_nudge(y = 1),
            data = italy_us_df)
fig4

Tis is not ideal. You can barely see the text. We should probably find a better way. The better way is called geom_label.

fig4<-ggplot(new_data3, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("Urbanization") + ylab("Life Expectancy")+
  ggtitle("Example Title")+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=FALSE)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
  geom_label(aes(label = Entity),
            size = 4, 
            position = position_nudge(y = 1),
            data = italy_us_df)
fig4

This is better. But still, which one is Italy and which one is the US?

library(ggrepel)
fig4<-ggplot(new_data3, mapping = aes(x=urbanization, y=life_expectancy)) +
  geom_point()+
  xlab("Urbanization") + ylab("Life Expectancy")+
  ggtitle("Example Title")+
  theme_bw()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=FALSE)+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=seq(0, 100, by = 20), limits = c(0,100))+
 geom_label_repel(box.padding = 0.5,
    aes(label = Entity),
            size = 4, 
            position = position_nudge(y = 1),
            data = italy_us_df)
fig4

So much better!
